                    <div class="a-column " id="a-col">
                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-157534 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-music des-music news_keywords-music" id="post-157534">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Understanding the Incomprehensible With Music</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Jeanann Pannasch			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-07-02T11:00:50+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 2, 2015 7:00 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 2, 2015 7:00 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I arrived home from the Shepherd Center in Atlanta &#x2014; a &#x201C;catastrophic care hospital&#x201D; &#x2014; debilitated by grief. I had many questions stemming from our family&#x2019;s new reality, but only one
                                        that I would work to answer: What should I include on a soundtrack for recovery for my formerly active and able-bodied 23-year-old nephew who had just become a quadriplegic? I sifted through my iTunes and the pile
                                        of neglected CDs shoved to the back of my closet with a clarity of purpose and swollen eyes. There wasn&#x2019;t much else I could do.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The accident occurred the day before Easter Sunday. Steven had gone off-road riding in his raised, customized Jeep Wrangler, with a young woman. They were good friends interested in something more. After they finished
                                        traversing the rocky terrain near his home in northern Alabama, Steven decided to tear around in a few doughnuts. Unfortunately, he didn&#x2019;t register that he had already unbuckled his seatbelt. As the monstrous
                                        Jeep spun around it caught an edge. The Jeep flipped &#x2014; and the roll bar landed across Steven&#x2019;s neck.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Steven sustained a spinal cord injury at his second cervical vertebra, just below where the skull attaches to the neck. He needed an emergency tracheotomy and was placed on a ventilator. His airway was entirely obstructed.
                                        A feeding tube was inserted through his stomach. He was blind in one eye, had low vision in the other. His larynx was crushed; he could not speak. We communicated with him by reading his lips. Luckily, the woman
                                        was thrown free of the Jeep, and sustained only cuts and minor bruises.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I didn&#x2019;t listen to the doctors when they said that we shouldn&#x2019;t have expectations about his recovery; I was bloated with hope. Steven&#x2019;s spirit was unconquerable &#x2014; he&#x2019;d prevail. I returned
                                        to Atlanta with a pile of music to motivate a miracle. But Steven was not yet ready for the rehabilitation gym. He slept a lot between visits from the physical, respiratory and occupational therapists, the psychologist,
                                        the pulmonologist, the infectious disease doctor, the nutritionist, the assistive-technology technician and the physiatrist. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One day, when it was just two of us in his room, I&#x2019;d run out of things to say. I flipped through the CD case I had brought with me, containing the Foo Fighters, Green Day and the soundtrack to &#x201C;Rocky.&#x201D;
                                        I stopped on &#x201C;Live and Loud,&#x201D; a double-disc live album from Ozzy Osbourne that I had acquired years before when I worked at a music magazine. I had never listened to it. Steven knew of Ozzy Osbourne
                                        from the MTV reality show &#x201C;The Osbournes,&#x201D; which meant he knew of Ozzy as a mumbling burnout shuffling around in slippers, not the legendary frontman for Black Sabbath, adored by metal heads for decades.</p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/02/opinion/02private/02private-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/02/opinion/02private/02private-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/02/opinion/02private/02private-blog480.jpg" id="100000003776099"
                                                    width="480" height="474" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="474">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Berliac</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It certainly wasn&#x2019;t my music. As a kid, I was horrified by stories of Ozzy biting off the heads of bats at live shows. My Catholic upbringing had made me obsessed with concepts of good and evil. I was convinced
                                        that the devil tried to reach us through music. The heavy metal bands of that time &#x2014; Judas Priest, Black Sabbath and Dio, to name a few &#x2014; merged in my young mind under the heading of Doing the Work
                                        of Satan. And there I left them.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But here we were, in Room 211, in a place where life became dark, where severely broken bodies and spirits had to accept their individual tragedies: There was the kid who climbed an amusement-park ride in order to rescue
                                        trapped passengers, but fell; the guy who took a bullet in the stomach and now, unable to face his young wife, made her stand in the hallway outside his room; the man who became a quadriplegic from a motorcycle
                                        accident, only to learn a week later that his wife had left him and his grown son had committed suicide. I slipped &#x201C;Live and Loud&#x201D; into the player and closed the door.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The wheeze of the ventilator and the cyclical chug of the feeding tube disappeared as screams of rock idolatry and wild applause filled the room. Although the CD was technically an Ozzy Osbourne solo album, it featured
                                        some Sabbath songs. The music kicked in, dark and dirgy. The bass drum hit at the heart. The guitar sounded distorted and dense. It was perfect. Between songs, Ozzy egged on the crowd in his thick British accent,
                                        asking to see their &#x201D;cigarette lightaaaaaaas.&#x201D; The stadium erupted &#x2014; and Steven smiled wide. It was a big, bracing grin, what we had come to recognize as the way he now laughed. Without the
                                        ability to draw breath, he could no longer laugh or cry as he did before. In that instant, Ozzy Osbourne became the most significant person on the planet for me.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the weeks that followed I listened to Black Sabbath all the time. It became the soundtrack to my grief. The song &#x201C;Never Say Die,&#x201D; the title track off Sabbath&#x2019;s eighth studio album, became an
                                        anthem for me. Steven&#x2019;s condition was not improving. He battled fevers and infections and stomach issues related to the feeding tube. We learned that he would never be able to talk or eat again. As other
                                        patients in the rehab gym were learning to use slide boards that would enable them to move from their wheelchairs to other seats, Steven&#x2019;s occupational therapist put oversize checkers on a table in front
                                        of him and asked him to select a piece to move. He didn&#x2019;t respond.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the weeks and months passed, I went back and forth between Atlanta and New York. During the time that I was home in Brooklyn, I ran a lot. I started listening to the earliest Sabbath albums as I ran through Prospect
                                        Park. I loved the distinctive guitar tone, the implication of pain and agony in Ozzy&#x2019;s voice, the distorted blues, the lyrics of destruction and despair. I ran with rage and sorrow and the crazy notion that
                                        my movement and breath and love would inhabit Steven&#x2019;s body and bring him movement, even a little. These were my prayers now. I ran hard and I cried hard, sometimes at the same time.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Months turned into years and Steven remained unchanged. His sharp mind was forever a starting point with no ability for action beyond thought, beyond the acts of blinking or moving his lips. After Steven left the Shepherd
                                        Center and returned home, we found out that his had been one of the worst spinal cord injuries the facility had ever treated.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One day while running, I listened closely to the lyrics of &#x201C;Iron Man,&#x201D; and had to turn it off. Released in 1970, the song tells a post-apocalyptic tale of a robotic man who tries to warn people of impending
                                        doom, but no one will listen. He exacts a bloody revenge over being mocked. The song begins: &#x201C;Has he lost his mind / Can he see or is he blind / Can he walk at all / Or if he moves will he fall?&#x201D; The
                                        resonance of these lyrics within the context of Steven&#x2019;s condition was deeply painful. The song continues: &#x201C;Nobody wants him / They just turn their heads / Nobody helps him / Now he has his revenge.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Steven&#x2019;s best buddies stopped coming by years ago. As I sat beside his bed during my visits, he would mouth their names, and we&#x2019;d spend a lot of time communicating about their absence. I found this desertion
                                        incomprehensible. I shared with him the dreams I had had about the two of us confronting these &#x201C;friends&#x201D; together. I knew that wouldn&#x2019;t happen; I had to settle for the new definition of evil
                                        that they have given me.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Just days after the sixth anniversary of Steven&#x2019;s accident, I attended my first Black Sabbath concert. Now I was one of those fans screaming in the audience. I stood there heartbroken, but fearless. I stood there
                                        for me and Steven &#x2014; and the sign of the devil horns was ours.</p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
                                    <button class="button comments-button theme-speech-bubble"></button>
                                    <div id="sharetools-post-footer" class="sharetools theme-classic" data-shares="show-all|Share" data-url="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/02/understanding-the-incomprehensible-with-music/"
                                        data-title="Private Lives: Understanding the Incomprehensible With Music" data-description="The only way I could get through to my nephew, suddenly a quadriplegic, was with the dark, dirgy music.">
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="footer-tags">
                                    </div>
                                </footer>
